abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., July 1. -- Senator Mark A. Hanna has lent his aid in securing a law favored by the miners of the bituminous region. Last week a bill was passed at Harrisburg which, if it becomes a law, will compel the mine operators to weigh the coal before screening it, and pay the miners full weight. At present the miner is only paid for the coal passing over an inch and a half screen.

abstract: The growth of the German Navy since 1872 has been extraordinary. According to figures quoted in the Reichstag, the increase in naval expenditure since that date has been 527 per cent. The outlay of the North German Confederation in 1870 was only 1,201,000; in 1885 that of the German Empire stood at 2,119,000; while at the date of the Emperor William II's accession it was 2,700,000, which by last year had risen to 4,315,000.

abstract: Two policemen of the East One Hundred and Fourth Street Station were attacked by more than a score of boys last night at One Hundred and Third Street and Madison_Avenue. abstract: This famous "gin law," passed in 1736, is interesting as the earliest severe blow at liquor dealing among civilized nations. It levied a tax of 20s. a gallon on spirits, and a license of 50 for any one selling or dealing in it. And, being in advance of public opinion, it failed, much as other more stringent prohibition laws have failed in our own day.

abstract: The Roman pontiffs corrupted the calendar rolls -- for instance, ordaining special intercalculated days to favor a moneyed friend who wished to retain office. At last the seasons fell months out of time, so that the festival of Spring was celebrated in July. abstract: The Bushman divests himself of all his incumbrances; water vessels, food, cloak, assegai, and sandals are all left behind. Stark naked, except for the hide patch about his middle, and, armed only with his bow, arrows, and knife, he sets forth. The nearest ostrich is feeding more than a mile away, and there is no covert but the long, sun-dried, yellow grass, but that is enough for the Bushman.
